In C programming, you terminate a program by calling the `exit()` function at some point in your code. This function is part of the standard C library and is included in the `<stdlib.h>` header.

Here's a simple example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");

    // Terminate the program
    exit(0);
}
```

In this example, after printing "Hello, World!", the program will terminate.

The `exit()` function takes an integer as its argument, which can be used to indicate the reason for termination. A value of 0 typically indicates successful termination, while any other value might indicate an error or abnormal termination.

Remember that once `exit()` is called, the program will immediately end, and no further code will be executed.
